,{"type":"contributions","id":"43713"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101312"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department with severe pneumonia. She has moderate dementia and lives in residential aged care. Her advance care directive indicates she wants full active treatment. Her daughter visits daily and helps make decisions about her care. Her ex-husband, from whom she separated 10 years ago, lives interstate and maintains contact approximately every six months. He is not involved in her care. She has no legally appointed guardian.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following people should be approached first as the substitute decision-maker for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Public guardian","Daughter","Treating doctor","Ex-husband","Residential aged care facility manager"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edaughter\u003C/strong\u003E should be approached first as the substitute decision-maker. The daughter demonstrates a \u0027close and continuing relationship\u0027 with the patient through her daily visits and ongoing involvement in care decisions. This makes her an appropriate person to act as substitute decision-maker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResidential aged care facility manager\u003C/strong\u003E - Facility staff are not recognised substitute decision-makers under legislation\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPublic guardian\u003C/strong\u003E - Generally only becomes involved if there is no available family member or conflict between decision-makers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreating doctor\u003C/strong\u003E - Cannot act as both treating clinician and substitute decision-maker\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEx-husband\u003C/strong\u003E - Despite the long marriage, the relationship is now dissolved, contact is infrequent, and he is not involved in care\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn determining a substitute decision-maker, the concept of a \u0027close and continuing relationship\u0027 is crucial. The daughter visits daily and is already helping make decisions about her mother\u0027s care, demonstrating this relationship. The ex-husband, despite being previously married to the patient, does not demonstrate a close and continuing relationship as contact is infrequent and he is not involved in her care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the specific arrangements for substitute decision-makers may vary between different Australian states and territories, but generally follow similar principles regarding close and continuing relationships.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A substitute decision-maker is appointed to make healthcare decisions when a patient loses decision-making capacity.","The concept of \u0027close and continuing relationship\u0027 is essential when determining the appropriate substitute decision-maker.","Substitute decision-maker arrangements may vary between different Australian states and territories."],"references":["Australian Government. Advance care directive. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/palliative-care/planning-your-palliative-care/advance-care-directive","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","A Clear Path to Care     . Government of South Australia. SA Health. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/cf0ab5804a396c67aac7efb0cfc4074a/Part+3_Advance+Care+Directives+and+the+Consent+Act_Acts+detail+and+dispute+resolution+.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-cf0ab5804a396c67aac7efb0cfc4074a-nKKa4Oh"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83742"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83742"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T10:22:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T10:23:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101312"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"